# Blog Post {#blog-post}

Meta Title: Demonstrating Proof of Possession (DPoP): OAuth2 Security for FAPI 2.0 and Open Banking  
Meta Description: Learn how DPoP enhances OAuth2 security by binding access tokens to a cryptographic key. Ideal for FAPI 2.0, PSD2, and mobile apps, DPoP protects APIs against token theft and replay attacks \- without the complexity of mTLS.

In traditional OAuth2 flows, access tokens are like concert tickets: if somebody happens to find one, they can walk right into the concert \- it doesn‚Äôt matter who actually purchased the ticket. This design is simple, and fine for lower-security use-cases. 

OAuth bearer tokens work the same way \- and that makes them easy to steal. If an attacker steals a token (for example, from an insecure app or exposed network, or intercepts the API call), they can impersonate the user and access protected services until the access token expires.

RFC 9449 defines a way to bind access tokens to a cryptographic key instead of just trusting whoever bears the token.

We call this **Demonstrating Proof of Possession (DPoP)** \- and it‚Äôs a huge step forward in securing APIs, especially in open, mobile, and browser-based environments.

Key DPoP benefits include:

Preventing token theft: A stolen token alone is useless without the client‚Äôs private key. Even if an attacker obtains the token, it‚Äôs impossible to forge the matching DPoP proof.

Public clients and mobile apps: Unlike mTLS (which requires certificates and is hard to achieve in SPAs / mobile), DPoP works entirely at the application layer. Clients simply store a non-extractable key (such as via Web Crypto), and sign proofs so that mobile or SPAs can safely use OAuth without exposing keys.

Replay protection: Each DPoP proof JWT contains a globally unique ID and specifies the HTTP method and URL. This enables servers to detect if the proofs are being re-used, or being mixed and matched across different requests.

Going back to our concert ticket analogy \- It has a date, and a venue. Meaning it is not valid for reuse across the entire tour. And imagine that your name and date-of-birth was also printed on it, and you had to show your Passport or Driver‚Äôs license at the door to prove that the ticket is really yours. 

In this post, we‚Äôll explain how DPoP works \- both the core ideas behind it and how to use it in practice. We‚Äôll look at its utility across industries, and explain how API platforms like Tyk are adapting to support FAPI 2.0 ready ecosystems.

## The Problem with Bearer Tokens {#the-problem-with-bearer-tokens}

Bearer tokens are simple \- whoever holds the token gets access. This is convenient, but it introduces risks.

Token theft: If a token is leaked (via logs, browser storage, insecure APIs), an attacker can impersonate the user.  
Replay attacks: Tokens can be reused multiple times unless explicitly scoped and expired quickly.  
Mobile and browser vulnerabilities: Public clients can‚Äôt safely store secrets, leaving tokens vulnerable.

OAuth2 doesn‚Äôt have a built-in way to ensure that only the original client can use the token. Once issued, anyone with the token can use it. For low-value or short-lived tokens, this may be acceptable. But for anything sensitive \- like personal data, payment initiation, healthcare APIs \- it‚Äôs a problem.

## Enter DPoP: Binding Tokens to Clients {#enter-dpop:-binding-tokens-to-clients}

DPoP enhances OAuth2 by binding the access token to a cryptographic key. Instead of trusting the bearer, the system now trusts the holder of a private key.

| Feature | Bearer Token | DPoP Token \+ DPoP Proof |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Bound to Client | NO | YES |
| Replay Protection | NO | YES (nonce \+ URL) |
| Works with SPAs/Mobile | YES (but insecure) | YES |
| Requires TLS Client Certificates | NO | NO |

DPoP brings the simplicity of Bearer tokens, with the security of mTLS.

### But what about mTLS? {#but-what-about-mtls?}

Mutual TLS is the original gold standard for sender-constrained tokens, where both client and server validate each other‚Äôs certificates. It‚Äôs incredibly secure, but also operationally heavy.

It requires issuing and managing client certificates  
It is impossible for public clients, mobile apps and SPAs to implement, as they cannot store secrets securely.  
It introduces significant infrastructure complexity \- such as termination at edge proxies and TLS renegotiation.

In contrast, DPoP achieves similar guarantees at the application layer using request headers, without all the friction. It‚Äôs ideal for public, and semi-trusted clients, that cannot store or rotate X.509 certificates.

FAPI 2.0 allows both mTLS and DPoP as valid token binding methods. DPoP is often preferred for public clients, SPAs, and mobile apps where TLS certs are not practical.

## How DPoP works (step-by-step) {#how-dpop-works-(step-by-step)}

Here‚Äôs a quick sequence diagram which walks through the DPoP flow step by step.

![][image3]

```
DO NOT INCLUDE_ JUST FOR DIAGRAM GENERATION

sequenceDiagram
    participant Client
    participant AuthorizationServer as AS
    participant ResourceServer as RS

    Client->>Client: [1] Generate key pair
    Client->>Client: [2] Generate DPoP proof (JWT with public key)
    Client->>AS: [3] Request token with DPoP proof (includes public key)
    AS-->>Client: [4] Return access token (bound to public key)
    loop [5] For each API request (until token expires)
        Client->>Client: Generate fresh DPoP proof
        Client->>RS: API request with Bearer token + DPoP proof
        RS->>RS: [6] Validate token & DPoP proof
        RS-->>Client: Authorized response
    end

```

1. Client generates a key pair (asymmetric, e.g., EC P-256).  
2. Client generates an initial DPoP proof, embedding the public key in the JWT header.  
3. Client requests an access token, sending the DPoP JWT in the `DPoP` header.  
4. Authorization server issues a token, including a fingerprint of the key embedded within a cnf.jkt claim.  
5. For each API request, the client:  
   * Generates a fresh DPoP proof with a unique `jti`, `htm`, and `htu`.  
   * Sends the DPoP proof alongside the `Authorization: DPoP <token>` header.  
6. Resource server verifies:  
   * The DPoP JWT is signed by the correct private key.  
   * The token‚Äôs key binding matches the key in the DPoP JWT.  
   * The request URL and method match the DPoP proof.  
   * The nonce (`jti`) hasn‚Äôt been replayed.

## A Real-World DPoP Flow {#a-real-world-dpop-flow}

Let‚Äôs look at a practical example. Assume you have a JavaScript-based public client (e.g., a single-page app or mobile app) using Keycloak as your authorization server.

Step 1 \- Generate a DPoP key-pair client-side using WebCrypto or equivalent

```javascript
const keyPair = await crypto.subtle.generateKey(
  {
    name: "ECDSA",
    namedCurve: "P-256"
  },
  true,
  ["sign", "verify"]
);
```

Step 2 \- Create the DPoP JWT

```javascript
{
  "htu": "https://auth.example.com/token",
  "htm": "POST",
  "iat": 1680000000,
  "jti": "unique-uuid"
}
```

This JWT needs to be signed using the private key from step 1, and the public key in the JWT header as a JWK.

Step 3: Request an access token

In a public client (like a browser SPA), client credentials grant is not permitted.  
Instead, use Authorization Code flow with PKCE. For brevity, we are skipping ahead to the part where we are exchanging the authorization code for the access token.

```javascript
fetch("https://auth.example.com/token", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: {
    "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded",
    "DPoP": "<signed JWT>"
  },
  body: new URLSearchParams({
    grant_type: "authorization_code",
    code: "<auth_code>",
    redirect_uri: "https://your-app/callback",
    client_id: "your-client-id",
    code_verifier: "<your-code-verifier>"
  })
})

```

Step 4: Call the protected resource

```javascript
const dpopProof = await generateDPoPProof({
  htu: "https://api.example.com/resource",
  htm: "GET",
  privateKey,
  kid
});

fetch("https://api.example.com/resource", {
  method: "GET",
  headers: {
    "Authorization": "Bearer <access_token>",
    "DPoP": dpopProof
  }
})
```

## Why this matters for API Platforms {#why-this-matters-for-api-platforms}

DPoP isn‚Äôt just a nice-to-have‚Ä¶

### Banking and Fintech (Open Banking / PSD2) {#banking-and-fintech-(open-banking-/-psd2)}

DPoP and FAPI 2.0 are especially relevant in banking and fintech, where open banking initiatives mandate strong API security. In the EU‚Äôs PSD2 (Payment Services Directive) and UK Open Banking, APIs for account and payment data must implement ‚ÄúFinancial-Grade‚Äù OAuth profiles. In fact, FAPI is now the basis for almost all open banking and open finance standards around the world‚Äîincluding the UK (OBIE), Brazil Open Finance, and Australia‚Äôs CDR.

FAPI 1.0 Advanced (used by UK OBIE and Brazil) mandated mTLS (certificate-bound tokens). FAPI 2.0 now allows DPoP as an alternative. This gives banks and fintechs the flexibility to phase out complex client certificates and adopt simpler, application-layer binding. Open banking regimes like OBIE and Brazil‚Äôs OBB are updating toward FAPI 2.0, making DPoP support increasingly common.

These features align with regulatory expectations around strong customer authentication and consent management. By adopting DPoP, banks and fintechs can better protect against token replay and theft in high-risk environments like mobile banking and third-party aggregators.

### Healthcare APIs {#healthcare-apis}

Healthcare data is highly sensitive and subject to regulations like HIPAA and GDPR. Modern health APIs (e.g., SMART on FHIR) increasingly use OAuth2/OIDC. DPoP provides extra assurance by binding tokens to specific app instances. If a token is leaked (via device compromise or XSS), it can‚Äôt be reused elsewhere. DPoP isn‚Äôt mandated in healthcare yet, but it‚Äôs a strong fit for these kinds of APIs.

### Government and Public Sector {#government-and-public-sector}

Governments are also adopting high-assurance API standards. The OpenID Foundation notes that FAPI is now a nationwide standard in many regions. National open data and digital identity initiatives are increasingly aligning with FAPI. DPoP ensures that only verified apps can use issued tokens‚Äîcrucial for citizen identity, benefits, and voting APIs. It‚Äôs also well-suited to SPAs and mobile clients common in government apps.

## Conclusion, and next steps {#conclusion,-and-next-steps}

Bearer tokens are convenient \- but risky. Demonstrating Proof of Possession offers a better way. By binding tokens to keys and verifying proof on each request, DPoP strengthens API security without sacrificing usability.
